title: For Sale/Trade:  US Historical Society Roy Rogers Uberti Made Colt -- Commemorative Single Action Army Revolvers & Case
postcontent:
Make:  Most writings attribute this series of firearms to A. Uberti, but since the U.S. Historical Society Firearms Division was sold to America Remembers in 1994, no one remembers the actual manufacturer and no official information is available. This was manufactured in 1992.

Model:  Single Action Army 

Serial Number: 504 or 2500

Year of Manufacture: 1990 (per Fjestad’s “Blue Book of Gun Values”) 

Caliber: .45 Colt 

Action Type: Single Action Revolver with Side Loading-Gate Cylinder 

Barrel Length: 4 ¾” 

Sights / Optics: The front sight is a half round blade fixed to the barrel. The rear sight is a “U” groove milled into the top strap. 

Stock Configuration & Condition: The two piece natural stag horn grips exhibit only the natural variances in the material.  The grips rate in about Excellent overall condition. 

Type of Finish: Blue Barrel, Frame and Backstrap, Gold Plated Cylinder and Trigger Guard 

Bore Condition: unfired

Overall Condition: This handgun retains about 98% of its metal finish. Almost no signs of handling are present. The screw heads are sharp. The markings are clear. It has very MINOR cylinder wear.  Overall I would say it is still in excellent condition.

Mechanics: The action functions correctly. We did not fire this handgun. 

All the original Paperwork: This pistol comes in a lacquered hardwood display case with a Roy Rogers signature burned into the lid.  A brass keyhole is visible on the front edge and a full length hidden brass hinge can be seen on the rear edge. The inside of the case is lined in royal blue velvet. The floor of the case is a form fit compartment for the pistol and compression marks from contact with the revolver are evident in the velvet. The floor of the box sports a brass plaque which is engraved with a rope border and reads “Roy Rogers King of the Cowboys / Single Action Army .45” / an American Eagle Emblem / “United States Historical Society”. An ornate brass key is included which operates the lock. The case is in Excellent condition. 

Our Assessment: This is a Roy Rogers ‘King of the Cowboys’ commemorative Single Action Army revolver, issued in 1990 by the United States Historical Society. This is number 504 of 2500 produced. The cylinder is marked with an Italian proof mark and most writings list this series as being manufactured by A. Uberti. This is a reproduction of a 1st Generation Colt Single Action Army black power frame, with a set screw securing the cylinder pin. This pistol is finished in a deep blue with a gold plated cylinder and trigger guard. The left side of the barrel displays gold lettering which reads “U.S. Historical Society” and the right side reads “Roy Rogers King of the Cowboys”. A guitar with notes and two American Eagles adorn the left side of the frame, while a guitar with notes, an image of Roy Rogers and “1940”, a Circled “50” and “1990” are visible on the right side. The cylinder is gold plated and features three stars between each flute and a musical staff encircling the rear of the cylinder, with musical notes and “Happy Trails to You” visible within the staff. The pistol is in Excellent condition, exhibiting almost no evidence of handling and resides in a dark hardwood case which is also in Excellent condition. This is a very attractive display pistol, honoring Roy Rogers, perhaps the most beloved Singing Cowboy this country has ever known.

title: For Sale:  1916? Marlin Model 19S Take Down – 80%-90%+ Condition
postcontent:
I’m not a dealer or collector so I can’t really accurately assess the condition of this gun on the typical percentage scale. I can say that it’s a beautiful and functional piece that still has most of its original bluing. 

I took this gun to a recent gun show to get other’s opinions. I was told by most dealers I spoke with that this gun was in about 80%-90%+ condition, and would likely auction as a collector piece for around $1100. Most of the bluing is in good condition. You can view the higher resolution pictures on my dropbox site and decide the condition for yourself: https://www.dropbox.com/sh/75aspa95txtl4uj/AAC5bhc3pHBTndIAkotbt0Laa?dl=0

The first picture in the dropbox group named “Marlin Model 19S in the NRA National Firearms Museum” is NOT this gun that I’m selling. I included the photo to show what a very nice Marlin 19S looks like in the NRA museum. All other photos in the dropbox folder are of this piece that I’m selling. 

I do not know the precise age of this piece. It may be a post 1916 piece based upon the “A” in the serial number. The serial number is “A12720”. I searched the web but could not find an accurate age based upon the serial number. The last patent date stamped on the barrel shows “May 19 ‘08”. Perhaps there are experts out there who can more accurately determine the age.

This gun was purchased as a used gun by my father in about 1934 near Crabtree, Pennsylvania, from a neighbor. My father used and owned the gun since then. He passed away last year. Before he passed, he asked that I find a good home for it with someone who could appreciate it. He told me that everything was original, so, as far as I know, it’s all original. He always took excellent care of all of his guns.

Although the gun is fully functional and in beautiful condition, I’m selling it as a collectors piece. Marlin has issued warnings about the older Model 19’s stating that they should not be fired due to noted failures to achieve full lock up, their age and their inability to handle the pressures of modern loads, even short 2.5” or 2.25” 12GA loads.

If interested please contact John via ArmsList email or by phone or text at: four-8-oh two-oh-3 six-1-eight-five.

Located in Denver. No shipping. No trades please. Cash only.

title: For Sale:  Very Unique Lyman Plains Pistol .50
postcontent:
This has to be one of the best custom jobs Ive seen in a while.
If this were a .54cal... Id never let it go. But, alas, my collection does not include .50cal pieces and I just cannot get setup for a whole new caliber.

I was very content when I rust blued mine, but this has been antiqued to an extreme. Very nice form of rust bluing, its lightly pitted, very uniformly across the entire surface, even the end cap and the belt clip are done the same way.
It accents the dull brass and case colored lock very well.

Beyond that the grips has been fully hand checkered on this, the stained finish is not the best but it definitely rounds out the look on this one. Very nice.

Anyhow, I took it on a trade sight unseen thinking it was a .54. So away it goes.

The bore looks good, fairly bright when I shine a light down it. But again, I dont shoot .50 so I dont have any jags or brushes for a .50cal. It looks free of any major rust or pitting. Im sure you can get some dirty patches out of it... but definitely looks like a nice shooter.

I can ship if needed, give me a zip code and Ill give you a price

Can do a face to face anywhere in the Portland/Vancouver area

The CZ 527 American features a classic American pattern stock, a sporter-weight hammer forged barrel, a single set trigger and a recessed target crown. Designed to be used with optics, this rifle also ships with a set of 1" steel CZ scope rings.
The .221 Remington Fireball is a centerfire cartridge created by Remington Arms Company in 1963 as a special round for use in their experimental single-shot bolt-action pistol, the XP-100. Based on a shortened version of the .222 Remington, it is popular as a varmint and small predator round while also finding increasing use among target shooters.
Despite its smaller size, the .221 Fireball is capable of velocities nearly equal to that of the .222 Remington due to its higher SAAMI pressure. The maximum SAAMI pressure level for the .221 Fireball is 52,000 C.U.P. as compared to 46,000 C.U.P. for the .222 Remington.

title: For Sale:  VZ 98/22, 8mm Mauser (K98 Action)
postcontent:
I have a Czech made, BRNO VZ 98/22 Mauser rifle that I am looking to sell.  This rifle is very clean-bored, full-sized, with a smooth working bolt and Farsi rear site (to help with dating).  It sat in a box as a Persian contract, though it does have the classic "warhorse" patina on the wood.  The VZ 98/22 was one of the earliest made BRNO series of Mausers, and was of the full length style.  This particular rifle is fairly clean with cosmoline left in the firing pin removal tool (circle in rear of stock) and the bayonet mounting grooves.  (I live in a very humid section of town, and figured I'd leave a little in these spots when I was cleaning the rifle the first time, they seem to hold the most crap!)  

These Czech Mausers were all really well made, and having a full-size early production BRNO is something many collectors are interested in, so if thats you get in touch with me!  Their accuracy also makes them great shooters.  Asking 220 obo, and it comes with 30 rounds of 8mm (7.92x57mm) in ammunition cases and with clips.  Must have valid proof of residency and be willing to complete a bill of sale.

postcontent:
I have 187 pieces of 7.62x54R brass.  The cases are pulled down from Bulgarian ammo.  The ammo shot terribly but the brass cases are pretty nice!  They are berdan primed but the cases are brass.  Most of these are also NOT once fired - 150 have primers that are intact so they are ready to load.  The other 37 are once fired.  I have also chamfered and deburred all the case mouths. http://castboolits.gunloads.com/showthread.php?143855-Converting-Berdan-primer-pockets-to-Boxer
